<header>
	Look at the pie chart and complete the report by filling each gap with the past simple of the verb given in brackets.
</header>
	
<section id="body">
	<img class="rightFloat" src="../Media/Unit01_Write_e5.jpg" mode="1" id="1003"  /><p align="left"><font color="#000000">In 1961 people in the UK mostly <input id="1" width="100" /> (watch) television or <input id="2" width="100" /> (listen) to the radio in their leisure time. On average they <input id="3" width="100" /> (spend) almost half of their free time on these activities. After that <input id="4" width="100" />(come) other unspecified pastimes, which <input id="5" width="100" /> (take up) about an hour and a quarter a day. People <input id="6" width="100" /> (not seem) to socialise a great deal, as this <input id="7" width="100" /> (account) for only 35 minutes in a typical day. People <input id="8" width="100" /> (eat) out, <input id="9" width="100" /> (go) to the cinema or <input id="10" width="100" /> (entertain) themselves in other ways outside the home for an average of 28 minutes a day. Finally, people <input id="11" width="100" /> (play) sports or <input id="12" width="100" /> (walk) for an average of only 9 minutes a day.</font></p><p align="left"><font size="2"></font></p>
</section>
<section id="rt2001">
	<p align="left">When a bar chart or pie chart has information relating to a single point in time in the past and does not show changes, we can mostly use the past simple to describe it.</p>
